    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Finding Hope in Knowing the Universal Capacity for Evil'' (Conversation, April 3): Philip G. Zimbardo is right in applying lessons from his legendary Stanford Prison Experiment to the atrocities of Abu Ghraib. But he mischaracterizes the broad findings of psychological research when he states: ''Human behavior is more influenced by things outside of us than inside.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Finding Hope in Knowing the Universal Capacity for Evil'' (Conversation, April 3): Philip G. Zimbardo is right in applying lessons from his legendary Stanford Prison Experiment to the atrocities of Abu Ghraib. But he mischaracterizes the broad findings of psychological research when he states: ''Human behavior is more influenced by things outside of us than inside.''</p>
        <p>Thirty-five years after his study, scientific research conclusively documents the predictive power of things inside the person. Among the most important predictors of violent crime, for example, include age, gender, low intelligence and low scores on traits of conscientiousness. The variation in the behavior of the 12 Stanford guards alerts us to the fact that human behavior is nearly always a function of the interaction of the inside stuff with the outside environment.</p>
        <p>Dan P. McAdams  Evanston, Ill.</p>
      </block>
